    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-05-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-05-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="299"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d299">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 839.00/1238.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Chargé d’Affaires of the Dominican
                            Republic</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                        State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation—Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 44.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dominican Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-05-19">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 19, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Secretary:</hi>
                </p>
                <p>I again refer to the subject of my note of the 14th instant to the Department and
                    have the honor to acknowledge receipt of the Hon. Mr. Lansing’s courteous note
                    dated the 16th, informing me that the Government of the United States recognizes
                    the blockade of Puerto Plata and refrains from doing so in the case of Monte
                    Christi until it hears that that blockade is effective.</p>
                <p>I have fresh instructions in this respect pursuant to which I have the honor to
                    inform you that my Government has decided for the present to confine the
                    blockade to the port of Puerto Plata thus leaving that of Monte Christi open to
                    commerce.</p>
                <p>I avail myself of this opportunity to express to the Department the thanks of the
                    Dominican Republic for the attitude maintained by the Government of the United
                    States.</p>
                <p>I renew [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">I. A. Cernuda</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
